poem:
The Printerjam

In printhour, when the rollers creak and fumble-gleam,
And tray-sprites wheeze in winding queues that slip and seam;
All deskfolk bumble by the feed with breath and bated thumb,
Beware the Jamjaw, rumblecrimp and drum!

Beware the Jamjaw, clerk of mine! The teeth that crimp and snag!
The curl that snap-fangs catch, the tray that tugs and nag!
Shun fuser-fiends and sprocket-snaps and toner-bitten blight!

He seized his spanner-sabre, lean, and leaned toward the maw;
He peered into the crooked chute where folded papers gnaw;
Left tug, right pry—he plucked the knot of crimped and clattery night,
And, as the Printerjam unbent, it gave a slobber-sight.

One-two! One-two! Through nip and nap he tore;
He wrestled folded leaf and spit the crumpled core;
He flicked the lever—clack!—the rollers sighed and stilled their jams;
He flung the final scrap away, and quelled the Jamjaw's clams.

Back hummed the trays with orderly streams of black on white anew;
He bore the printout bounty home; the toner-smile grew true;
"O trumple day!" the office sang, "the duplex flows again!"
And all the stapled pages lay without a wrinkle's reign.

The Musicroomwock

’Twas brumpling in the music-room, the candle-gong did swing;
The tablorn sighed on velvet rails, the metronomes did cling;
All mimsy were the harp-snarks, and the windlish flutes aflute;
Beware the Musicroomwock, my child, the beast of bolted lute!

He strode to where the piano-reef lay snoring, keys all white and black,
And in the corner, brash and bulb, the Bassjaw opened slack;
Its brassly teeth went tootle-grin, its cymflaps broke the air;
It hummed the hollow, clanging thrum of counterpoint despair.

“O father, see the timp-snout rise, the cello-spine undulate!”
The bowlings hissed, the strings did stitch a skein of syncopate;
But forth he went with strum-sword drawn — a gleaming quarter-note —
He whistled low a glimmer-song and struck the organ-throat.

The Musicroomwock did shudder-snap, its valves in whirlpools span,
It frothed a hundred fandangoes, it staggered, staccato-fanned;
He pluckled there a bravely chord, a tremor, twine, and swoop,
Till Bassjaw flung his last bass-bream and sank to timbre's loop.

And then! — the shelved-scores, they danced; the metronomes they beamed;
The harp-snarks winked their silver tongues; the flutelets softly dreamed;
“O son! the Musicroomwock is felled! the studio is free!”
He brought the tune-home, blythe and blest, a victor's vibrato-glee.

So when the lamp-gongs brumple low and midnight keys conspire,
Beware the hush that swells to roar, the monster's minor fire;
But arm yourself with steady hand, with cadence, pulse, and pluck—
The Musicroomwock will falter, felled by one true struck.
